@startuml
!include ../../styles/plantuml-theme.puml

left to right direction
title FIG-13-01. Online Store SysML-style Requirement Traceability View\nSimplified, non-normative teaching view

skinparam rectangleRoundCorner 8
skinparam rectangle<<Requirement>> {
  BorderColor #175CD3
  BackgroundColor #EEF4FF
}
skinparam rectangle<<Design>> {
  BorderColor #175CD3
  BackgroundColor #F7F9FB
}
skinparam rectangle<<Verification>> {
  BorderColor #B54708
  BackgroundColor #FFF7E6
}
skinparam rectangle<<Evidence>> {
  BorderColor #027A48
  BackgroundColor #ECFDF3
}

' Column 1: Requirements
rectangle "REQ-OS-01\n----\nCheckout shall not store full\ncustomer card details in the\nOnline Store." <<Requirement>> as R1
rectangle "REQ-OS-02\n----\nThe customer shall receive an\norder confirmation after the\norder is accepted." <<Requirement>> as R2
rectangle "REQ-OS-03\n----\nSupport users shall view order\nstatus without seeing full\npayment details." <<Requirement>> as R3

' Column 2: Design responses
rectangle "Payment Provider System\ndelegation: the Online Store\nstores only payment status and\nprovider reference." <<Design>> as D1
rectangle "Order record and confirmation:\nthe order service creates the\norder record and triggers web\nor email confirmation." <<Design>> as D2
rectangle "Masked support view: the\nsupport interface shows order\nstate and masked payment\nstatus only." <<Design>> as D3

' Column 3: Verification cases
rectangle "Verify card-data storage\nboundary during checkout." <<Verification>> as V1
rectangle "Verify accepted-order\nconfirmation." <<Verification>> as V2
rectangle "Verify support-role access to\nmasked payment information." <<Verification>> as V3

' Column 4: Verification evidence
rectangle "Security test result and\nprovider integration review." <<Evidence>> as E1
rectangle "Functional test result and\nmessage-log sample." <<Evidence>> as E2
rectangle "Access-control test result and\nsupport-role review." <<Evidence>> as E3

' Requirement addressed by design response
R1 --> D1 : addressed by
R2 --> D2 : addressed by
R3 --> D3 : addressed by

' Requirement verified by verification case (direct, not via design response)
R1 --> V1 : verified by
R2 --> V2 : verified by
R3 --> V3 : verified by

' Verification case evidenced by verification evidence
V1 --> E1 : evidenced by
V2 --> E2 : evidenced by
V3 --> E3 : evidenced by

' Hidden ordering keeps columns left to right:
' Requirement | Design response | Verification case | Evidence
D1 -[hidden]-> V1
D2 -[hidden]-> V2
D3 -[hidden]-> V3

legend bottom
Element types (shown as stereotypes): Requirement, Design (design response), Verification (verification case), Evidence.
Left to right: Requirement | Design response | Verification case | Evidence.
addressed by connects a requirement to its design response. verified by connects a requirement
directly to its verification case. evidenced by connects a verification case to its evidence.
A trace is a navigable claim for review. It does not prove that the requirement is satisfied,
that the implementation is correct, or that verification passed.
endlegend

@enduml
